formal_statement:
import Mathlib

open Real Set
open scoped BigOperators

/- Let \[f(x) = \left\{
\begin{array}{cl}
2x + 7 & \text{if } x < -2, \\
-x^2 - x + 1 & \text{if } x \ge -2.
\end{array}
\right.\]Find the sum of all values of $x$ such that $f(x) = -5.$ -/
theorem algebra_11063 {f : ℝ → ℝ}
  (hf : ∀ x, x < -2 → f x = 2 * x + 7)
  (hf' : ∀ x, x ≥ -2 → f x = -x ^ 2 - x + 1) :
  ∑ᶠ x ∈ {x | f x = -5}, x = -4 := by

soln_description:
Solution. After performing the exponentiation and subtracting $x^{4}$:

$$
8 x^{3}+24 x^{2}+32 x+16=y^{3}
$$

Since 8 is a cube, let $8 b^{3}=y^{3}$, thus

$$
\begin{aligned}
8 x^{3}+24 x^{2}+32 x+16 & =8 b^{3} \\
x^{3}+3 x^{2}+4 x+2 & =b^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Transform the obtained equation:

$$
(x+1)^{3}+(x+1)=b^{3}
$$

Now let $a=x+1$, thus

$$
\begin{aligned}
a^{3}+a & =b^{3} \\
a\left(a^{2}+1\right) & =b^{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

Since $a$ and $a^{2}+1$ are relatively prime, $a\left(a^{2}+1\right)$ can only be a cube if both $a$ and $a^{2}+1$ are cubes. This is only possible if $a^{2}=0$ and $a^{2}+1=1$. Therefore, $x+1=0$, so $x=-1, y=0$.

